5000|$|Ice forms rapidly when {{liquid is}} readily available. When liquid is readily available, the {{segregated}} ice (<b>ice</b> <b>lens)</b> grows {{parallel to the}} exposed cold surface. It grows rapidly until the heat liberated by freezing warms the <b>ice</b> <b>lens</b> boundary, reducing the temperature gradient and controlling the rate of further ice segregation. Under these conditions, ice grows {{in a single layer}} which gets progressively thicker. The surface is displaced and soil repositioned or rock fractured.|$|E
5000|$|Freezing and thawing {{of the ice}} {{produces}} {{masses of}} <b>ice</b> (<b>ice</b> <b>lenses).</b>|$|R
